media:group.media:title: NEWS.am daily digest: 29.10.21
media:group.media:description:
Armenian News - NEWS.am presents the daily digest of Armenia-related top news as of 29.10.21:
SOLDIERS https://news.am/eng/news/669746.html At around 10 am on Thursday, four servicemen were lightly wounded as a result of careless handling of ammunition at the military base of a military unit located in an easterly direction of Armenia. The Ministry of Defense informs Armenian News-NEWS.am that first aid was immediately provided to these wounded. An investigation is underway to fully find out the circumstances behind this incident.
EU https://news.am/eng/news/669819.html Starting from Friday, October 29, Armenia is considered a very high risk area in terms of the coronavirus pandemic, hence new regulations for traveling to the Netherlands from Armenia have been imposed, informed the Embassy of the Netherlands in Armenia. The European entry ban is in effect for some people, barring them from traveling to the European Union (EU) or the Schengen area. Entering the Netherlands is allowed if the purpose of the trip falls under one of the exemption categories.
AIRLINE https://news.am/eng/news/669832.html The Civil Aviation Committee of Armenia on Wednesday issued FLYONE ARMENIA airline an aircraft operator’s license in the country, Armenian News-NEWS.am has learned from this airline. Thus, FLYONE ARMENIA has become a national operator and will soon be ready to start its first passenger flights. FLYONE ARMENIA has invested more than 60 million euros in Armenia’s passenger aviation market. Also, the airline plans to create more than 135 jobs with above-average salaries. The airline's fleet consists of Airbus A320 aircrafts. From Yerevan, FLYONE ARMENIA will operate flights to Moscow, Tehran, Lyon, Kutaisi, Damascus, Krasnodar, Paris, Istanbul, and Tel Aviv. FLYONE ARMENIA will start selling its airline tickets soon.
UNESCO https://news.am/eng/news/669850.html The latest—2021—the issue of Living Heritage magazine of UNESCO has been published, the Ministry of Education, Science, Culture and Sports informs Armenian News-NEWS.am. This issue is dedicated to the 75th anniversary of UNESCO, and it presents the challenges of preserving the intangible cultural heritage in Southeastern Europe. In this connection, the magazine extensively covers the intangible Armenian cultural heritage, too.
COVID-19 https://news.am/eng/news/669826.html As of Friday morning, 2,096 new cases of the coronavirus were confirmed in Armenia, and the total number of these cases has reached 304,546 in the country. Also, 43 more deaths from COVID-19 were registered, making the respective total 6,232 cases.
